The paper discusses the problem of learning large-scale probabilistic representations from structured and unstructured data, which is a common topic in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The use of natural language processing techniques to extract unstructured data suggests that the paper may also fall under the category of computational linguistics (cs.CL). The paper also discusses the limitations of the closed-world assumption, which is a topic in cryptography (cs.CR) and information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper proposes a new approach to learning tractable probabilistic models, which may fall under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI).
